{{also|falloff|fall-off}}
==English==

===Etymology===
From {{af|en|fall|off|nocat=1}}; and also dissimilated from {{der|en|enm|offallen|t=to destroy, defeat, ruin, fail}}, from {{der|en|ang|offeallan|t=to fall upon, destroy}}.

===Verb===
{{en-verb|fall<,,fell,fallen> off}}

# {{lb|en|transitive|and|intransitive}} To become [[detached]] or to [[drop]] from.
#: ''A button '''fell off''' my coat.''
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1900|author=L. Frank Baum|title=The Wonderful Wizard of Oz|chapter=23|passage=Dorothy stood up and found she was in her stocking-feet. For the Silver Shoes had '''fallen off''' in her flight through the air, and were lost forever in the desert.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[diminish]] in [[size]], [[value]], etc.
#: ''Business always '''falls off''' in the winter.''
#: ''MC ___'s new album is wack - he's '''fallen off''' big-time.''
#* {{quote-av|en|year=2021|author={{w|Lil Nas X}}|title=THE MONTERO SHOW|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TZ0-Cdtj4KU|text="Ratio. YoungBoy is better." "What?" "Make better music. You '''fell off'''."}}
# {{lb|en|nautical}} To change the direction of the sail so as to point in a direction that is more down wind; to bring the bow leeward.
#* '''1846''', Melville, ''Typee'', [[s:Typee/Chapter 1|chapter 1]]
#*: 'Why d'ye see, Captain Vangs,' says bold Jack, 'I'm as good a helmsman as ever put hand to spoke; but none of us can steer the old lady now. We can't keep her full and bye, sir; watch her ever so close, she will '''fall off''' and then, sir, when I put the helm down so gently, and try like to coax her to the work, she won't take it kindly, but will '''fall''' round '''off''' again; and it's all because she knows the land is under the lee, sir, and she won't go any more to windward.'
#* '''1854''', [[w:Benjamin Robbins Curtis|Benjamin Robbins Curtis]], ''Lawrence v. Minturn'', [[s:Lawrence v. Minturn/Opinion of the Court|Opinion of the Court]]
#*: She would not mind her helm, but would '''fall off'''; she would settle down aft and take in water over her stern, and plunged heavily forward.
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1886|translator=H.L. Br&aelig;kstad|author=Peter Christen Asbj&oslash;rnsen|authorlink=Peter Christen Asbj&oslash;rnsen|title=Folk and Fairy Tales|page=182|passage=The pilot-boy, who was on the look-out forward, and was keeping the boat from '''falling off''' by using the starboard oar, as the current went in a westerly direction, answered that he thought "it went a little easier forward."}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1898|author=Kipling|title=[[s:The Burning of the Sarah Sands|The Burning of the Sarah Sands]]|passage=There was the constant danger of the ship, now- broadside on to the heavy seas, '''falling off''' before the heavy wind, and leading the flames forward again.}}

